Q:

Can you use an if then in an object initializer, or do you need to use a block?

Can you do this:
UIView *myView = [[UIView alloc] initWithMyValue:myParameter? YES:NO];

Instead of this:
UIView *myView = [[UIView alloc] initWithMyValue:myParameter];
if (myParameter) {
    myView = nil;
}        

A:

You can definitely do it like this, but note that you shouldn't rely on this. Since the method returns an object at the end, the default value will only exist for the time the method executes. Then it gets returned to the pool and can be used by someone else at any time.
If you know your object will stay allocated for the length of the app, then this would make sense, but otherwise it really only makes sense if you are initialising a large number of UIViews, and you know the number at compile time, or it's small enough you could just precheck all of them using the code in the first example.

