The barrier function of the skin consists of keratinocytes that are surrounded by a complex three‐dimensional network of extracellular matrices (ECM). The first barrier of the body is to protect from the outside world, and the skin has both mechanical and chemical components to provide this barrier. Amongst chemical, components of the skin are important not only for protection but also for temperature regulation, pheromone transport and the perception of pain and touch. In addition, skin harbours other components of the immune system (such as Langerhans cells) and it is the skin that carries immunologists, when studying tolerance to self, transplantation or autoimmune diseases, to the first immune defence system of the body. Since its discovery, the skin has served as a useful research model to study human immune system development. The development and homeostasis of the immune system in the skin has revealed to be as complex as in the entire body. There exists a large variety in different cell types, a huge degree of plasticity and a plethora of soluble factors that control immune cells homeostasis within the skin: the epidermal layer hosts a large variety of immune cells

